					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 607.0, 126.0, 151.0, 409.0 ],
					"presentation" : 1,
					"presentation_linecount" : 30,
					"presentation_rect" : [ 573.0, 127.0, 151.0, 409.0 ],
					"text" : "When waves overlap or are summed together (for instance when two signals are both sent to the same place) the amplitudes are simply added together.  When a positive part of a signal interacts with a negative part of a wave, they cancel out.\n\nWhen waves with the same shape but a slightly different frequency sum together the result is beating, in which the differences between the two waves creates an alternation of reinforcement and cancellation.  Waves which are 1Hz apart will cycle through reinforcement and cancellation 1 time per second.  In other words the beating will produce 1 \"beat\" or amplitude throb , per second.  Waves 2Hz will beat twice a second."
				}

			}
